snippet.textDisplay: I've had an idea for a LCD/OLED hybrid TV for a long time.  The LCD would be used like it normally is, but the OLED would only be used as a backlight. I don't understand why no TV manufactures have tried this.

snippet.textDisplay: The first laptop I had was an original Clevo. The only branding hat had was no branding but rather a big "NOTEBOOK" written on the display cover. It had a Pentium 4HT with 3.06GHz (if i recall correctly), 512MB (later upgraded to 1GB) of ram and Radeon 9700 graphics with 128MB VRam and a surprisingly high resolution 4:3 display at 1400x1050. The thing had about 80 minutes of battery life, even with light usage and it got so hot that the CPU regularly clocked down to 1.4GHz (until I changed thermal paste), which when it happened caused CS 1.6 to run in slow motion. It was loud, fast, kinda crappy in buildquality and I loved it

I used to have a Clevo, bought it second from someone for a fraction of the price after they couldn't get used to the qwerty keyboard layout (We use azerty here)

Best laptop I ever owned, an absolute beast in specs and weight.
Too bad it broke due to its own rigidity; The hinges were so strong, they eventually snapped the chassis on both sides and replacements were 160 euro/side.

Continued to use it after ductaping some brackets to the back and bottom of it, but I eventually replaced it. Never came across one since sadly.

snippet.textDisplay:
If you want the ABSOLUTE PINNACLE OF DISPLAYS it's a technology called nano-RGB-laser-emitter where MONOCHROMATIC red, green and blue lasers are modulated to a given power level and emitted from a 200 nanometer-sized dot fitted into a CMOS well which is glued onto a metal, ceramic or plastic backplate. The electrical trigger signal lines are etched via electron beam (or a CO2 laser) to give each pixel a SINGLE path to an off-board controller.

This means that each tri-dot RGB laser emitter well can switch from NO-power (i.e. fully black) to full ON (bright white) within 50 Nanoseconds! This means the display assembly is physically capable of up to TWENTY MILLION FRAMES PER SECOND!

ON a practical basis, this technology, when applied in modern imaging applications, gets up to 10,000 frames (TEN THOUSAND HERTZ) at resolutions as high as 131,072 by 131,072 pixels at 64-bitsper pixel RGBA colour! Since the laser can be modulated to almost ANY in-between power-level, the number of luminance levels can be up to 32 bits per RGB channel (96 bit RGB colour) or QUADRILLIONS of colours which NO HUMAN EYE can ever hope to differentiate!

It's so powerful that each emitter needs a micro neutral density filter to keep the laser power levels EYE SAFE (i.e. so as to NOT burn our retinas!)

AND since the colour Red is wavelength of about 700 nanometres, it means you need RGB emitters of that size minimum or about 2500nm by 2500nm for the typical 3x3 photo-emitter-site RGB array used for a single combined pixel. This also includes enough room for the electrical line trace widths for each pixel, so it means your maximum possible pixel density is between 900,000 to ONE MILLION pixels per inch!

However, on a COST-EFFECTIVE BASIS, you generally "Print" these RGB 3x3 emitter arrays at about 2400 dots per inch so for a typical 32 inch diagonal gaming display that is about 27.5 inches by about 15.5 inches in width and height, you will have a resolution of UP TO 66,000 pixels horizontal and 37,200 pixels vertical!

NOW THAT A TRULY HIGH RESOLUTION DISPLAY!

.

These types of nano-emitter displays have been in research labs for about 10 years now and are JUST STARTING to be put into head mount displays, micro-projector systems and the first 32 inch displays for really high end satellite imaging tasks. They tend to be around $250,000 U.S. for a 32 inch display at 64k resolution! We are probably about 6 to 8 years where a 1000+ fps at 32 inch 64k resolution nano-RGB laser display will be available for general purpose use at a price below $10,000 U.S. !!!

.

snippet.textDisplay:
I genuinely did know about Clevo before this; I bought one of their laptops way back in 1997 or 98. Full-sized desktop Pentium 1 CPU in it, making the whole thing thick as hell. Had an active-matrix LCD though, great screen for the time. I literally had to take out a small loan to buy it, which was unwise in retrospect but didn't turn out to be a problem and I got my money's worth out of it. It shipped with a buggy GPU driver on the CD that came with it though, that was a bastard to figure out at the time. Crashed the whole system until I updated it from the one on the (very early & primitive) web page.


So question about micro-LED vs. OLED - in theory, would a 1:1 LED to LCD-pixel screen be better than an OLED screen?
